{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f628cb06-79d5-456b-8dc9-41cd101fc372","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2**, which supports constructor injection. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Constructor — sync init + TestContext injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // synchronous setup here\n    }\n\n    // Async init\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitAsync()\n    {\n        _service = await MyService.CreateAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Hello from test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_service);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points (MSTest v3):**\n\n- **`TestContext`** is injected via the **constructor** — the old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern still works but constructor injection is preferred.\n- Use the **constructor** for synchronous setup.\n- Use **`[TestInitialize]`** returning `async Task` for asynchronous setup.\n- Avoid `async void` — always return `Task`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"20b31cef-c717-4e4a-bf18-611e70b90ddf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In MSTest v3, the recommended approach for initialization has evolved. Let me provide guidance on the modern patterns.\n\nIn MSTest v3 (3.x), key changes:\n1. `TestContext` can be injected via constructor (no need for the property setter pattern).\n2. You can use `[TestInitialize]` for sync init and `[TestInitialize]` also supports async (returns `Task`).\n3. Constructor can be used for synchronous initialization.\n\nThe recommended modern pattern in MSTest v3:\n- Use the **constructor** for synchronous initialization and `TestContext` injection.\n\n\n- Use `[TestInitialize]` with `async Task` for asynchronous initialization.\n\nThe old pattern relied on property injection for `TestContext`, but the new approach in v3 uses constructor injection for `TestContext` and separates sync initialization in the constructor from async initialization in an `[TestInitialize]` method that returns `Task`.","outputTokens":575,"requestId":"CFC2:2D9C3A:6165969:6CE6C8C:69EC176F"},"id":"f016ac24-38ed-4b43-b516-9e6372be3d93","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:23:07.012Z","parentId":"1cf3015e-8915-4441-a961-6fdc86f4288d"}
